    {
      "id": "jHZ-o74F6GkWZdEnoIBef",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5923.844669098265,
      "y": 3282.45502611026,
      "width": 1328.79833984375,
      "height": 780,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0N",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1873465289,
      "version": 1185,
      "versionNonce": 484849769,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1780769941443,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. How do you handle billions of users?\n\n- To handle billions of users, I would horizontally scale Chat Servers behind a load balancer. \n- This creates a routing problem because users may be connected to different servers. \n- To route messages between servers, I'd use Redis Pub/Sub. \n- Before publishing a message, I would persist it in the Message Table and create Inbox entries for recipients. \n- Redis Pub/Sub provides real-time delivery to online users, while the Inbox Table guarantees eventual delivery for offline users when they reconnect. \n- This separates real-time messaging from durable storage and allows the system to scale horizontally\n\n- Should we partition by chat or by user?\n    - Since WhatsApp traffic is dominated by 1-to-1 conversations, \n    - I would partition Pub/Sub channels by user rather than by chat. \n    - This keeps subscriptions low because each connected user requires only one channel subscription. \n    - When a message is sent, the sender's server publishes to the recipient's user channel, and the receiving server forwards it via WebSocket.\n    \n    - Senior-Level Optimization\n\n        - There is a special case: Large Group Chats\n        \n          - Adaptive Strategy\n\n            - Small chats:\n                - Use user channels\n\n            - Large chats:\n                - Use chat channels\n\n          - Example:\n\n            If participants < 25\n                publish to user channels\n\n            If participants >= 25\n                publish to chat channel\n\n\nFor a WhatsApp-style system, I'd partition Pub/Sub by user because most conversations are 1-to-1, which minimizes subscriptions. \nFor very large group chats, I may switch to chat-level channels to reduce the number of publishes, using a hybrid strategy based on group size\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. How do you handle billions of users?\n\n- To handle billions of users, I would horizontally scale Chat Servers behind a load balancer. \n- This creates a routing problem because users may be connected to different servers. \n- To route messages between servers, I'd use Redis Pub/Sub. \n- Before publishing a message, I would persist it in the Message Table and create Inbox entries for recipients. \n- Redis Pub/Sub provides real-time delivery to online users, while the Inbox Table guarantees eventual delivery for offline users when they reconnect. \n- This separates real-time messaging from durable storage and allows the system to scale horizontally\n\n- Should we partition by chat or by user?\n    - Since WhatsApp traffic is dominated by 1-to-1 conversations, \n    - I would partition Pub/Sub channels by user rather than by chat. \n    - This keeps subscriptions low because each connected user requires only one channel subscription. \n    - When a message is sent, the sender's server publishes to the recipient's user channel, and the receiving server forwards it via WebSocket.\n    \n    - Senior-Level Optimization\n\n        - There is a special case: Large Group Chats\n        \n          - Adaptive Strategy\n\n            - Small chats:\n                - Use user channels\n\n            - Large chats:\n                - Use chat channels\n\n          - Example:\n\n            If participants < 25\n                publish to user channels\n\n            If participants >= 25\n                publish to chat channel\n\n\nFor a WhatsApp-style system, I'd partition Pub/Sub by user because most conversations are 1-to-1, which minimizes subscriptions. \nFor very large group chats, I may switch to chat-level channels to reduce the number of publishes, using a hybrid strategy based on group size\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "tJfQ1yOfYFrwHR4-ONKBs",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5948.889260554423,
      "y": 4159.564295268296,
      "width": 536.7992553710938,
      "height": 660,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0R",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 674031079,
      "version": 187,
      "versionNonce": 1337857223,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780772841468,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. What do we do to handle multiple clients for a given user?\n\n- Track Devices(Clients) Separately\n    Instead of:\n        - User\n    We introduce:\n        - Client (Device)\n\n- New Clients Table\n    | clientId | userId | device |\n    | -------- | ------ | ------ |\n    | c1       | B      | Phone  |\n    | c2       | B      | Laptop |\n    | c3       | B      | Tablet |\n\n- Now we know:\n    - User B has 3 devices/ clients\n\n- Update Inbox Table\n    \n    - Old:\n         | userId | messageId |\n         | ------ | --------- |\n         | B      | m101      |\n   \n    - New:\n        | clientId | messageId |\n        | -------- | --------- |\n        | c1       | m101      |\n        | c2       | m101      |\n        | c3       | m101      |\n    \n    - Note: One inbox entry per device",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. What do we do to handle multiple clients for a given user?\n\n- Track Devices(Clients) Separately\n    Instead of:\n        - User\n    We introduce:\n        - Client (Device)\n\n- New Clients Table\n    | clientId | userId | device |\n    | -------- | ------ | ------ |\n    | c1       | B      | Phone  |\n    | c2       | B      | Laptop |\n    | c3       | B      | Tablet |\n\n- Now we know:\n    - User B has 3 devices/ clients\n\n- Update Inbox Table\n    \n    - Old:\n         | userId | messageId |\n         | ------ | --------- |\n         | B      | m101      |\n   \n    - New:\n        | clientId | messageId |\n        | -------- | --------- |\n        | c1       | m101      |\n        | c2       | m101      |\n        | c3       | m101      |\n    \n    - Note: One inbox entry per device",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "mbsbgZ1LsR7BIEKDdTOZH",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5388.621188806678,
      "y": 4191.780689111803,
      "width": 580.7991943359375,
      "height": 200,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0W",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1213678025,
      "version": 85,
      "versionNonce": 1427037993,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780772718896,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Sender sends message.\n2. Store message in Message Table.\n3. Find recipient users.(Query chatParticipant table using chatId)\n4. Find all recipient clients/devices.\n5. Create Inbox entry for each client.\n6. Publish via Redis Pub/Sub.\n7. Deliver to all online devices.\n8. Each device ACKs independently.\n9. Delete Inbox entry only for that specific device.\n10. Offline devices receive messages when they reconnect.",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Sender sends message.\n2. Store message in Message Table.\n3. Find recipient users.(Query chatParticipant table using chatId)\n4. Find all recipient clients/devices.\n5. Create Inbox entry for each client.\n6. Publish via Redis Pub/Sub.\n7. Deliver to all online devices.\n8. Each device ACKs independently.\n9. Delete Inbox entry only for that specific device.\n10. Offline devices receive messages when they reconnect.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "LbZ09DXyKknCLje6FVMLX",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -4594.363799381571,
      "y": 4199.3735036770495,
      "width": 343.19952392578125,
      "height": 440,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0Z",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1960146921,
      "version": 114,
      "versionNonce": 1334093001,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780772829433,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Alice sends message\n        |\n        v\nFind participants using ChatParticipant\n        |\n        v\n[Alice, Bob, Charlie]\n        |\nRemove sender\n        |\n        v\n[Bob, Charlie]\n        |\nFind devices using Devices/client table\n        |\n        v\n[d1, d2, d3]\n        |\nCreate Inbox entries\n        |\n        v\nDeliver message",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Alice sends message\n        |\n        v\nFind participants using ChatParticipant\n        |\n        v\n[Alice, Bob, Charlie]\n        |\nRemove sender\n        |\n        v\n[Bob, Charlie]\n        |\nFind devices using Devices/client table\n        |\n        v\n[d1, d2, d3]\n        |\nCreate Inbox entries\n        |\n        v\nDeliver message",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "PW5x5761KaOhfrhSiO2fh",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5430.814377702579,
      "y": 4512.132149231273,
      "width": 677.5990600585938,
      "height": 180,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0a",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 456220681,
      "version": 102,
      "versionNonce": 1017512425,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780772832588,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "In the multi-device design, we do one extra step: find the reciepient devices\n\nRecipient Users\n      ↓\nRecipient Devices\n      ↓\nInbox Entries\n      ↓\nMessage Delivery",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "In the multi-device design, we do one extra step: find the reciepient devices\n\nRecipient Users\n      ↓\nRecipient Devices\n      ↓\nInbox Entries\n      ↓\nMessage Delivery",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
