      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 707058825,
      "version": 418,
      "versionNonce": 2000985193,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780773822490,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Clients\n\nClient/Device\n- clientId\n- userId\n- ClientType",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "proD8ubufX3844wLeUNBn",
      "originalText": "Clients\n\nClient/Device\n- clientId\n- userId\n- ClientType",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "UQf9WTrXIG4krqsTY4Uwq",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5871.434713080836,
      "y": 5582.502452653864,
      "width": 809.598876953125,
      "height": 280,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffffff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1F",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1718677993,
      "version": 71,
      "versionNonce": 1135244615,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780906066484,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "3. What happens if the WebSocket connection fails?\n- TCP timeouts are too slow and can take minutes.\n- We can use ACK timeouts:\n    - Server expects an ACK after sending a message.\n    - If ACK isn't received after several retries, close the connection.\n- To detect failures even when no messages are being sent, use application-level heartbeats:\n    - Server sends periodic `ping` messages.\n    - Client responds with `pong`.\n    - Missing pong indicates a dead connection.\n- Once a connection is considered dead:\n    - Close it.\n    - Client reconnects.\n    - Chat Server loads pending messages from the Inbox.\n    - Missed messages are delivered.",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "3. What happens if the WebSocket connection fails?\n- TCP timeouts are too slow and can take minutes.\n- We can use ACK timeouts:\n    - Server expects an ACK after sending a message.\n    - If ACK isn't received after several retries, close the connection.\n- To detect failures even when no messages are being sent, use application-level heartbeats:\n    - Server sends periodic `ping` messages.\n    - Client responds with `pong`.\n    - Missing pong indicates a dead connection.\n- Once a connection is considered dead:\n    - Close it.\n    - Client reconnects.\n    - Chat Server loads pending messages from the Inbox.\n    - Missed messages are delivered.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "_ekGs0KJAAMSw-6EBOJQu",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5982.365983456168,
      "y": 5922.767162119076,
      "width": 853.5988159179688,
      "height": 740,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffffff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1H",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1911019655,
      "version": 116,
      "versionNonce": 20387369,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780921259253,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "4. What happens if Redis fails to deliver a message?\n- Redis Pub/Sub is at-most-once delivery, so an online user may miss a message if Redis drops it.\nSolution:\n1. Persist every message in the Message Table and Inbox Table before publishing.\n\n2. The Chat Server requests the next sequence number from an atomic\n   counter (e.g., Redis INCR).\n\n3. The Chat Server attaches that sequence number to the message before\n   persisting and publishing it.\n\n4. The sequence number is included in every message sent to the client.\n\n5. The client tracks the highest sequence number it has received.\n\n6. Heartbeat pings include the server's latest sequence number for that user.\n\n7. If the client detects a gap (e.g., receives 103 after 101) OR\n   the heartbeat sequence is greater than its local sequence,\n   the client requests a sync.\n\n8. The Chat Server checks the Inbox table for missing messages.\n\n9. The Chat Server sends the missing messages to the client.\n\n10. The client renders messages based on sequence number (or server timestamp),\n    not network arrival order.\n\nFinal Summary\n\n    Message Table + Inbox Table  -> Durability\n    Redis Pub/Sub                -> Real-time delivery\n    Sequence Numbers             -> Detect missed messages\n    Heartbeats                   -> Fast detection of gaps\n    Inbox Sync                   -> Recovery mechanism\n\n",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "4. What happens if Redis fails to deliver a message?\n- Redis Pub/Sub is at-most-once delivery, so an online user may miss a message if Redis drops it.\nSolution:\n1. Persist every message in the Message Table and Inbox Table before publishing.\n\n2. The Chat Server requests the next sequence number from an atomic\n   counter (e.g., Redis INCR).\n\n3. The Chat Server attaches that sequence number to the message before\n   persisting and publishing it.\n\n4. The sequence number is included in every message sent to the client.\n\n5. The client tracks the highest sequence number it has received.\n\n6. Heartbeat pings include the server's latest sequence number for that user.\n\n7. If the client detects a gap (e.g., receives 103 after 101) OR\n   the heartbeat sequence is greater than its local sequence,\n   the client requests a sync.\n\n8. The Chat Server checks the Inbox table for missing messages.\n\n9. The Chat Server sends the missing messages to the client.\n\n10. The client renders messages based on sequence number (or server timestamp),\n    not network arrival order.\n\nFinal Summary\n\n    Message Table + Inbox Table  -> Durability\n    Redis Pub/Sub                -> Real-time delivery\n    Sequence Numbers             -> Detect missed messages\n    Heartbeats                   -> Fast detection of gaps\n    Inbox Sync                   -> Recovery mechanism\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "EMpQjewPXEsadmEbBxyyC",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5962.990613694916,
      "y": 6694.583637975036,
      "width": 589.5991821289062,
      "height": 440,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffffff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1K",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1976447559,
      "version": 6,
      "versionNonce": 161670631,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780921677410,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "5. Problem:\nMessages can arrive out of order because of network delays,\nmultiple Chat Servers, retries, and Pub/Sub behavior.\n\nDo we guarantee perfect ordering?\nNo.\n\nReason:\nGuaranteeing strict ordering requires buffering and waiting\nfor late messages, which increases latency.\n\nSolution:\n1. Synchronize Chat Server clocks using NTP.\n2. Stamp each message with a server timestamp when received.\n3. Send timestamp/sequence number with the message.\n4. Clients display messages sorted by timestamp or sequence number,\n   not by network arrival order.\n\nResult:\nMessages appear in a consistent order across all clients.\nOccasionally a late message may \"pop in\" above another message,\nwhich users generally find acceptable.",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "5. Problem:\nMessages can arrive out of order because of network delays,\nmultiple Chat Servers, retries, and Pub/Sub behavior.\n\nDo we guarantee perfect ordering?\nNo.\n\nReason:\nGuaranteeing strict ordering requires buffering and waiting\nfor late messages, which increases latency.\n\nSolution:\n1. Synchronize Chat Server clocks using NTP.\n2. Stamp each message with a server timestamp when received.\n3. Send timestamp/sequence number with the message.\n4. Clients display messages sorted by timestamp or sequence number,\n   not by network arrival order.\n\nResult:\nMessages appear in a consistent order across all clients.\nOccasionally a late message may \"pop in\" above another message,\nwhich users generally find acceptable.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "wYY8ZRKnl4TqBMXob3QaQ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -5957.857268640444,
      "y": 7238.7182137489835,
      "width": 457.599365234375,
      "height": 600,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffffff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1L",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 303893671,
      "version": 10,
      "versionNonce": 1674073671,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1780923089490,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How can we handle a \"last seen\" functionality?\n\nBad Solution:\n    Update lastSeen timestamp on every heartbeat.\n    Causes millions of writes per second.\n\nBetter Solution:\n    Store only the user's last disconnect timestamp.\n\nFlow:\n\n1. User connects.\n   - No database write.\n\n2. User disconnects.\n   - Chat Server updates LastSeen table.\n\n3. Another user requests last seen.\n\n4. Chat Server:\n   a) Reads LastSeen table.\n   b) Publishes a request via Redis asking whether\n      the target user is currently online.\n\n5. If the target user's Chat Server has an active\n   WebSocket connection, it responds with ONLINE.\n\n6. Client shows:\n   - ONLINE if online response arrives.\n   - Otherwise shows last disconnect time.",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How can we handle a \"last seen\" functionality?\n\nBad Solution:\n    Update lastSeen timestamp on every heartbeat.\n    Causes millions of writes per second.\n\nBetter Solution:\n    Store only the user's last disconnect timestamp.\n\nFlow:\n\n1. User connects.\n   - No database write.\n\n2. User disconnects.\n   - Chat Server updates LastSeen table.\n\n3. Another user requests last seen.\n\n4. Chat Server:\n   a) Reads LastSeen table.\n   b) Publishes a request via Redis asking whether\n      the target user is currently online.\n\n5. If the target user's Chat Server has an active\n   WebSocket connection, it responds with ONLINE.\n\n6. Client shows:\n   - ONLINE if online response arrives.\n   - Otherwise shows last disconnect time.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
